description.text: An .STL and 123D design file for some feet for the Shapeoko CNC router.

Print out 4 of these and use your favorite fasteners/adhesive to securely fasten your Shapeoko to the cutting platform.
A friend of mine recently built his own Shapeoko CNC router.  He was having problems with it sliding/vibrating around his table as he tried to cut parts.  So I whipped up some feet for it, and now his router stays firmly attached to the table while he is cutting.
*NOTES:  My friend said that M5 hex caps work wonderfully for clamping the feet to your Shapeoko, the hole is 4.5mm across so they thread right into the plastic.
Also due to the desire to maintain a small footprint, you will need to mount the feet to the base platform first.  Well, really it's only an issue if you are using full height socket cap screws.  If you use button style or low profile socket cap screws you should be fine assembling it in whatever order you fancy.

title: Ring of focused leds for Hephestos 1- v2

description.text:
I re-designed the led ring to achieve two goals:

  • having the light emitted by the leds focused on one point, near the hot-end
  • being able to use the 12v power supply of the hephestos without wasting power in a resistance.

Upgraded version where I cut parts of the ring to fit better aside the hot-end

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

10 %

To have only one spot of light centered where the hot-end supplies its stuff, I defined holes for the leds all converging to a central point located at the center of the ring, and about 10mm under it.
To reduce power wasting, and heat dissipated in a resistor, I choose to connect the leds in a serial manner, rather than in parallel, as shown in the second picture. Each white led defines a dropout voltage of 2.6v. The whole set defines a dropout voltage of 10.4v. The common current is about 20mA. The resitor needed to reduce 12v to 10.4v, with a 20mA current is about 100 ohms. And the power dissipated remains very small.
If you use led of standard colors, the dropout voltage is smaller, around 1.4v. You have to change the resistor value according to the new global dropout voltage.

The picture under show how the top part fits perfectly to protect the inside wiring and the leds, without glue. You just have to press firmly on it to insert the small blocks of the top into the groove of the ring.

title: Tool Holder for Metal Spudger Set

description.text:
I keep a set of scraper and prying tools near my 3D printer to use in a variety of different ways. They are useful for everything from digging out support material on prints to prying apart bowden tube connectors on the printer.

To keep them organized, I designed this holder. The holder was specifically designed for the tools I have:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B015K7KQ92/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

The holes in the base/backer plate are designed to take a number 6 flat head screw. This allows the holder to be screwed to a surface. Alternatively, something like Command Strips could be used to mount it.

The bottom hooks are larger than the rest. This set is for holding the spudger with the curved heads. The curved heads means the tools cannot sit as close to the backer plate as the other tools.

I printed this in PLA with PVA support material.

I used a larger wall thickness than I normally do so that the support hooks would print mostly solid. This was done to get as much strength as possible out of them. I recommend something in the neighborhood of about 2.3 mm. The bases of the hooks (where they connect to the backer plate) will not be solid at this setting, but rest of the hook will be.

I increased the support footprint size to get a little more surface area for the support material attachment. I've had issues with support material with a small footprint getting knocked over. In Cura, this setting is called "Support Horizontal Attachment." Something around 1 mm should work.

title: TBS Event Tracker 3/4" PVC Mount

description.text:
Slapping your TBS Event Tracker on the ground creates undesirable reception and makes tracking LESS accurate than having the Event Tracker elevated. I designed this mount to sit on a 3/4" pvc pipe which I put behind a gate.

Designed to be printed out of TPU - I imagine this could work out of a rigid filimant, but then you'd have to slide it over the end of the PVC instead of being able to slip it over the pipe in the middle.

The Event Tracker sits behind the top panel of the gate protecting it from direct hits, and the mount allows it to move if hit to help dissipate energy and not break anything. I also mount the ET with the USB ports and network jacks facing away from oncoming traffic so if it does get hit the case of the ET is taking the brunt of the force, not electronics.

The top platform can be used to strap a lipo to, or POE boxes as shown.

description.text:
This design is based upon a design of a similar jig posted on YouTube by user "Shop Built". The video was great (I just wish he didn't have the video running so fast as it made it difficult to discern what he was doing). Anyway, while I recognized that this project was daunting as a woodworking project. it was just begging to be a 3D printer project... sooooo...

This is my first attempt at designing and 3D printing on the Lulzbot TAZ 6. These parts are prototypes which means that they were printed using the "High Speed" setting in Cura. The filament I used was 1.75 mm True Black Polylite PDA. I got the 1.75 mm filament by accident and then found out through some extensive Googleing that the Lulzbot TAZ 6 (and I believe the TAZ 5 with the hexagon hot end) will work with 1.75 filament, all you have to do is use the profile for Polylite PDA (or other if using a different filament) and switch the size to 1.75 in the advanced setting dialogue box.

Here is what a kerfmaker is and what it does (skip ahead to the 4:30 mark if you're not interested in seeing this made of wood); https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YsfOWa_TFR8&t=173s

I ordered the knurled low profile thumb nuts from here; https://www.mcmaster.com/#92815A115

The threaded parts are 1/4-20 x 1/2" long and 14-20 x 1" long (I couldn't find a set screw that long so I modified a bolt to work).

This is a soccer player who can be controlled by a cellular under Android OS. You can build it and then play with your acquaintances as you could play table soccer.

I uploaded all 3d model archives in stl format. Some pieces need to be assemble by a strong glue. This was necessary because some pieces couldn't be printed with a 3D FDM printer as a whole piece. Support imperfections.

This robot is perfect for kids between 10 and 12 years old.

Please, before building and printing, read all instructions below. I don't want you to waste plastic and then blame me :-)

Of course, this project needs more updates in order to have a perfect one, as we can already find bugs in this version. Support is required, just in case, you want to help us ;-].

description.text:
READ THE WHOLE DESCRIPTION.
USE THE LATEST VERSION STEP OR F3D, NOT THE STLs.
Versions indicated are STEP file versions.
Files named "cherub shell" actually contain the entire blaster. Sorry for the confusion.
Okay. now that that's over with, I'll start by saying real blasters have curves. I put over 6 hours of design time into this, but no more than 7 (as of v2). Be impressed if you want, I don't find it particularly fast. 6 whole hours? That's a long time.

Update to v3: Mag now sits lower in the blaster by 0.1". Mag now slips into place without having to hold down the release lever. All solids named appropriately rather than numerically. Springs are far less likely to slip out of place. (I still recommend adding a small nub with an OD equal to the ID of your spring wherever a spring goes, or using hotglue to hold the springs in place.)

I now also have included a multibody STEP file of the left half of the shell (the two halves are symmetrical) cut up into 120mm by 120mm blocks to fit most printers.

Update to v4: screws added where needed (edit: yeah no they were needed a ton of other places too), priming rod is now two pieces that screw together. Screws are 4-40x1/4". Pump grip screws together now (yay) Haven't figured out screw ports for the shell yet. It's gonna need a lot of them. Also, I forgot to include the PH, so use the PH from the v3.

Update to v5: Holy crap. Lots of new mounting holes, and an actual way to put the two shell halves together.

Update to v[all the screws] / v20.f3d: Again, holy crap. Lots of mounting screws. All 38 of them are now in place. (edit: who'd'a thought, I actually missed 6 but no biggie.) Also, realized the height offset on the mag was too much, so reduced from 0.1" to 0.05". Pusher would hit the upper mag lips if you printed anything from v3 to v5. So don't print the v3, v4, or v5.

Update to v7: Jam door-ish-thing created, picatinny rail added. Mags still fit too tight, will fix that soon.

Update to v8: A few good fixes. Mag fit is fixed, and the problem of the mag release catch not catching is also fixed. Spring retention on the mag release is improved.

Cherub v[all the screws] parts needed list

1x90273A106 Screws. Depending on your choices, you may need a lot of these. They are small, and a lot of them are needed to hold the blaster together tightly.

1x9637K25 Main spring: This gives you enough for 5 cherubim. A Longshot upgrade spring will also work, as well as a K26 (I'm pretty sure, you may need to shorten the PR guide some) I use a stock LS spring and a Century C-836 because it's what I have.

1x9657K266 Catch spring/mag release spring. Gives enough for 6 cherubim, and appropriate springs can easily be salvaged from dead blasters.

1x9176T7 This is the main PT tube. The rear end of the PT must be wrapped in packaging tape, shimming it to almost a 2 inch diameter. Gives enough for 5-6 cherubim.
(Note: with a new PH model and o-ring, the blaster can accommodate a 1.75" ID PT as well.)

1x 9667K55 This is the best wire I could find for the application. it will be hard to bend to make the trigger, but other than that it's glorious. Gives enough for a lot of cherubim.
But honestly, any .125" steel wire will do as long as it's not super soft or weak for some reason.

1x9558K559 or other o-ring of the same dimensions.

1x8978K14 This type of tube can be found cheaper at most hardware stores, typically in 3 foot lengths.

1x8978K17 or CPVC for the plunger rod. If you happen across magic CPVC, you can reinforce it with a solid 1/2" rod of anything you can cut/file/sand that's rigid, or with the above 1/2" OD tube.

K&S 8140 or 9117 tubing (17/32" OD) for the barrel. 8140 is 12" long, 9117 is 36" long.

For people who mod their Mazzer Doser grinders, e.g. Super Jolly or Major, this is a cap to cover the center nut / bolt / screw to keep it neat and clean.

I would recommend you print with a brim instead of a skirt to give the first 10mm or so better bed adhesion.

It's an articulated desk lamp, composed mainly of 3d printing pieces. Measures approximately 35 cm high in natural position and 50 cm fully stretched.

The parts are divided for better printing. The base of the lamp is composed of two pieces, the main part which is hollow to add some element that gives weight. They can be coins, stones, or some heavy object. And a extra part that covers it.
The lamp hood is separated into two parts and there is a third piece that holds the lamp holder. These pieces are joined by glue. (I upload the whole piece in case someone wants to print it as well)

The materials needed to complete the product are (see photo):
One led bulb (GU10)
Bulb holder
Coated cable (color choice) approximately 3 meters long
A plug
A switch
Three screws 5 mm in diameter
Three butterfly nuts for screws

Setting up the robot

After all the pieces have been printed you can assemble the robot as normal. You will need to use the midsection with servo mounts instead of the usual midsection. Before you have attached the head you should place two centered servos into the midsection's mounts. Attach the left servo to pin 3 and the right servo to pin 11. Once the robot is set up you can upload the code called "zipline_code" in the thing files.

Building The Zipline

The zip-line consists of two platforms and a line. The first platform should be up high and the second one should be down low and several feet away. The line should be very taut and about 9 inches above each platform.
For example you could use a table as the first platform, the floor as a second and some thin rope for the line.

From the beginning of the challenge I knew that I would need to design arms for the Chip-E. I started brainstorming different ways to attach the arms. I came up with the idea of attaching servos to each side of the robot's midsection. I started the modeling process by first designing mounts to hold the servos. I then attached the mounts to each side of the robot's midsection.

The next step of the designing this project was to make the arms. I wanted some different options so I designed two different arms. To make them I first measured all the dimensions that the arms needed to fit. Once the arms were modeled I put holes into the joints so they could be attached to the servos.

description.text: This is a stand to hold and display petropixels W16 engine http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:68806 . It holds it at either end and stops it rotating by holding it in three of the grooves at either side. There are also longer pins that come out of either end of the crankshaft which are needed to be used with the stand. I used the remixed crankshaft http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:70153 so these are the longer pins I have provided.

Simply print the W16 Stand.stl file and two of Longer Remixed Pins.stl. Insert the longer pins at either end of the crankshaft rather than the ones currently there, put the engine in the stand with the pins through the holes and reattach the handle to one of the pins. There will be a new file shortly which has the stand and two longer pins in one file for easier printing.
Does not require support, should print in less that 2 hours with a 0.2mm layer height and roughly 20% infill.

I've been printing for a couple of years now, and much like a young Jedi aspiring to become a master, I felt it was time to try to make my own printer.

I had a few goals for this project:

  • large print area with a relatively small footprint.
  • direct drive extruder (no corexy)
  • avoid rods and linear bearings where possible (z only)
  • use v slot for x and y (because i wanted to play with v slot)
  • use 2040 extrusion for stability.
  • recycle as much of my folgertech 2020 i3 as possible

The inspiration was the FT-5, along with some of the projects I collected in my 'i3 rework' collection here -- thanks to all of those people! Even if I didn't use a part directly, they helped shape the direction I was going to go with things.

Based on the FT-5, the things I changed the most were:

  • no melamine!
  • z motors connect directly to the rods, no belts to tighten
  • x/y use v slot gantries rather than slides.
  • the x bar sits on top of the printer -- the cube doesn't extend up over it

The parts are almost all from FolgerTech, with v slot stuff from open builds and assorted screws and such from Amazon.

This is a work in progress -- I haven't finished wiring it up, so who knows if any of this will even work... This light saber could come out more Kylo Ren than Luke Skywalker!

Once I see if it does stuff I'll post up the list of parts I used.

NOTE: "These are not the timing pulleys you want". No really, you want version 4, which is here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:36568 This is an OpenSCAD parametric model for making most any timing pulley that you need. It's designed to generate a model printable without support material (observing the overhang rule of thumb). You can configure it to fit the belt that you're using. The pulley can be fixed to a threaded shaft with a nut. On one side the nut (the setting for an M8 hex nut is configured for you already) will sink into the pulley. If you tighten a nut on the other side as well it will be very well fixed. Another option is to use set screws. You just specify the diameter of the screw and it will create a hub with a (capped) teardrop hole. The set screw option has been fixed in this version so that odd numbers of set screws (such as the very useful 3 set screw version) can be supported without the holes going out the back of the hub. An option has also been added to angle the set screws. The STL file included works well with the Synchroflex(R) timing belt,1500Lx10Wmm from RS (order code 474-5892), spliced in half (to 5 mm width). This way you'll have a very good belt driven system for about 4 euros per meter. The belt comes as a closed loop, but you may need to glue it to get it to the right length. Depends on teardrop.scad being placed in the MCAD folder. Won't always render with F5, use F6.

description.text:
Wanted to do something a little different with this tri-spinner as the 3+1 bearing spinners are pretty played out, IMO. I love the contrast between the cold, metal weights (copper welding tips) and the plastic arms; especially how you can see the weights inside and at the ends of the arms.

I used the center nub and rest from an Adafruit spinner file. You can print these in contrasting or complementary colors to add your specific design flair. You may have to slightly file the outside of the shaft of the nub to get it through the center of the bearing. Then just push it through, put a small dab of CA glue on top (don't get it on the bearing), push the other end on, and then keep pressure on it for a little while to let it dry. I use a C-clamp and keep it on there overnight.

Model is set up for 608 skateboard bearings. They are just a press fit (works best while the body is still warm, but you can just gently tap them into place using a hammer. I use a wrench socket to put the force on the outside of the bearing (not across the balls themselves). I happened to use hybrid ceramic in my latest builds (can't justify the cost of fully ceramic), but honestly prefer a good ss ball and race. I prep by removing the dust seal and use graphite powder, work it in, and then blow it clean using an air gun, which also helps to polish the race as it spins at high speed. Protect your eyes and be wary of weights that may become dislodged and fly across the room!!!

Weights are 11-35 (0.035") MIG welding contact tips that can be purchased at your local hardware store. Glue the weights in using CA glue (Cyanoacrylate glue, aka "super glue"). The edges around the ends of the weights are pretty thin and can be broken when installing the weights or when the spinner is dropped. I have clipped these parts off on some of my spinners and the glue is more than strong enough to keep the weights in place.

Hope this helps someone. If you have any tips or make any changes, please let me know as I'd be interested in seeing what others do with my design.

description.text:
This is a quick n' dirty mount setup for putting a Bondtech BMG extruder on the excellent extruder from jasonatepaint. Possibly other direct-mounted extruders as well.

The extruder is only fastened to the mount by the groove-neck so you need reasonably good dimensions on your printed part.

Before fitting the BMG extruder, install the mount, put a PTFE tube down the E3D-V6 and put a mark 2mm above the mount, cut it, and it'll mate perfectly once the BMG is in place.

I have used this for half a roll (0.5kg) so far, and it's seems sturdy enough!

description.text:
This is a remix of Fidget Flower with bearings by craeen

I love the idea of hiding weights inside a fidget spinner, especially when using nuts. However, after printing the original flower I quickly realized that it was not well balanced. I opened the design in SketchUp and found that the design has no symmetry (some petals are longer, some petals are closer together, etc.). Also, the nuts moved around a tiny bit in their cavity.

I redesigned the flower "from scratch" using the look of the original, while making each of the five petals symmetrical. I also converted the inner cylinders into the hex shape of the 5/16" nuts. The center post helps with bridging across the cavity.

description.text:
This is a replacement for the original LM8UU Rostock carriages.

Before: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nmRD8YZUZBs
After: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2vjd2sL3d-A

Make sure your Printer is well calibrated.
I sliced in cura with these settings:
0.2mm layer height
0.8mm wall thickness
0.8mm bottom/top thickness
50% infill
45mm/s print speed
80mm/s infill speed
Unfortunately i don't know how to use openSCAD, so i measured the original carriages and rebuilt it in Inventor as good as i can.
There are some differences, so you have to calibrate your printer (at least CARRIAGE_HORIZONTAL_OFFSET) again.
After you have printed them, carefully run an 8mm drill through the bearings (works better if you spin it the wrong way).
Then run a 3mm drill through the U-Joint screw holes.
Before installing, put some grease or oil on the bearings to lubricate it.

Couldn't figure out whether I wanted to make a dodecahedral or tetrahedral puzzle, so this seemed like the obvious choice! It's a simple Face-Turning Dodecahedron (colloquially, a "megaminx") transformed into the shape of a tetrahedron. The "pillowing" effect is necessary, had I used a regular tetrahedron, pieces would either fall out or collide mid-turn. Rather than pillow the shape via my usual method, I used a Reuleaux Tetrahedron, which has the interesting property of always being of constant-width.

I do a lot of computer work and often I need to work with Hard drives outside the parent system various reasons. I've tried USB docks and they can be hit and miss and clutter up the desk. So I designed this dock to sit in the space of 2 5.25" bays and allows you to slide in 3 of any size SATA hard drive.
For the cables I used a set of cheap generic combination cables from ebay and designed the housing to fit them with just a bit of movement to allow for alignment. The screws to retain the cables were just your typical hard drive mounting screws.

I had to design it in 2 pieces to save on support material. Depending on your printer accuracy the tab and notch may need a little filing to get to fit properly and some crazy glue will hold it all together.

I hope it can be of use to someone else as its been a godsend for me in my work.

description.text:
RulletShot is a fun drinking game for parties or reunions.
The rules are really simple: You sit arround the RulletShot, then place the shot glass on top of it and spin the selector. The one who is selected has to do the shot. After that you repeat as many times as you want.

How to build it

To build this game you'll need the 3 printed parts plus a skate bearing (measures in the image above), a plane rubber circle and a circular metal weight.

STEPS

  1. The bearing is inserted into the selector middle hole under preasure.
  2. The circular metal weight is superglued into the selector's cavity.
  3. The plane rubber circle is superglued into the inferior bodypart cavity.
  4. The cilinder part on the top of the inferior bodypart is inserted under preasure through the middle hole of the bearing.
  5. The superior bodypart is superglued with the inferior bodypart.

Solidworks Design

The 2 bodyparts were designed using the revolution mode, while the selector was designd using extruding mode and cut/extrude mode.
In both cases the edges were rounded.

R.O.B. the robot was an accessory for the Nintendo Entertainment System released in 1985. The toy came bundled with the game Gyromite as well as a bunch of accessories used to play the game.

Less common is "Stack-Up", a separate game with its own accessories which required to be purchased separately. The set consisted of the game cartridge, a set of 5 colored "blocks", 5 stand pieces to install in the R.O.B. base and two hand grip attachments.

What's included in this project:

  • block-v1.stl
    The block piece. Print 5 of these in following colors: blue, red, green, yellow, white.

  • rob-base-v4.stl
    The base pieces. Print 5 in white/pearl color for best effect.

This project is an attempt at creating replacement parts for R.O.B. Currently blocks and stands are available with the grips arriving shortly. These can be easily temporarily replaced with a piece of sponge and a couple rubbber bands.

Parts are designed to be printable without supports or rafts but some printers may need supports for the angled stand pieces.

I used a DaVinci Jr. to print my samples and they work perfect, but some adjustments might be required for different brands. For my settings please check the "Print Settings" box.

The original R.O.B. blocks weigh around 8-9 grams. The replacements, as printed with my settings weigh about 12 g. This doesn't seem to affect the operation of ROB but if your robot struggles to lift the entire weight of all the blocks, try reducing the infill.
